<glossary title="Glossary Example by faqxml" version="1.0" date="2014-05-24" 
    sorted="true" alphahead="true" toplinks="true">

<glossentry glen-id="vitruvius" sortkey="vitruvius" topickey="Classical Orders"> 
<status>published</status> 
<comment></comment>
<glossterm>Vitruvius</glossterm> 
<glossdef> 
Marcus Vitruvius Pollio was an architect and engineer of the first century BCE. His book <emphasis>De Architectura</emphasis> summarises classical architecture.</glossdef> 
</glossentry>

<glossentry glen-id="corinthian-column" sortkey="column" topickey="Ancient styles"> 
<status>published</status> 
<comment>Brief description to start; this needs to be expanded</comment>
<glossterm>Corinthian column</glossterm> 
<glossdef> 
Corinthian columns are slender and fluted. Their capitals are bell-shaped decorated with acanthus leaves. See also <glenref refid="doric-column"/></glossdef> 
</glossentry>

<glossentry glen-id="doric-column" sortkey="column" topickey="Ancient styles"> 
<status>published</status> 
<comment>Brief description; this needs to be expanded</comment>
<glossterm>Doric column</glossterm> 
<glossdef> 
Doric columns are stout, typically 6 to 7 times as tall as the diameter at the base. See also <glenref refid="corinthian-column" linktext="column of the Corinithian order"/>.</glossdef> 
</glossentry>

<glossentry glen-id="orders-classical" sortkey="orders" topickey="Classical Orders"> 
<status>published</status> 
<comment></comment>
<glossterm>Orders of classical architecture</glossterm> 
<glossdef> 
There are five classical orders: Ionic, Doric, Corinthian, Tuscan and Composite. <link url="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_architecture">Read more at Wikipedia</link>.</glossdef> 
</glossentry>

</glossary>
